No external library at all — it's the browser's built-in Web Geolocation API, which is part of standard HTML5 and available in every modern browser with zero imports.

Just one native call:

javascript
navigator.geolocation.watchPosition(onGpsUpdate, onGpsError, options)
That's it. The browser handles everything — asking for permission, getting the fix from WiFi/cell tower triangulation or GPS hardware, and pushing updates. Nothing to install, no API key, no CDN link.

Then for the road data — OpenStreetMap via Overpass API:

javascript
fetch('https://overpass-api.de/api/interpreter', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: 'data=' + encodeURIComponent(query)
})
Again no library — just a plain fetch() call to a free public server. OpenStreetMap is the open-source alternative to Google Maps, and Overpass is its query API. No account, no API key, completely free for reasonable use. The query returns JSON describing every road, school, playground, crossing within the radius you specify.

So the entire road context AI feature is:

Web Geolocation API — built into the browser, zero setup
Overpass API — free public HTTP endpoint, zero setup
speechSynthesis — also built into the browser, zero setup
No npm, no Python, no server, no keys. That is why it was so easy to add — everything was already available in the browser you were already using.

