Same story — no external API, everything built into the browser.

Web Speech API — two parts, both native:

javascript
// Speech recognition (microphone → text)
const rec = new SpeechRecognition() // or webkitSpeechRecognition in Chrome
rec.lang = 'en-US'
rec.onresult = e => console.log(e.results[0][0].transcript)
rec.start()

// Speech synthesis (text → voice)
speechSynthesis.speak(new SpeechSynthesisUtterance('Hello'))
That is literally everything. No API key, no server, no account.

How it actually works under the hood — this is worth knowing for your thesis:

For recognition, Chrome does send your audio to Google's servers to transcribe it. It is not fully on-device. That is why it requires internet and why it occasionally fails offline. Firefox uses a different backend.

For synthesis, the voices come from your operating system — Windows uses Microsoft voices, macOS uses Apple voices (Samantha, Daniel etc.), which is why the voice sounds different on different computers. Fully offline.

Why this matters for your thesis

You are using three browser-native APIs with zero dependencies:

Feature	API	On-device?
Voice recognition	Web Speech API	No — audio sent to Google
Voice synthesis	Web Speech API	Yes — OS voices
GPS location	Web Geolocation API	Yes — WiFi triangulation
Road data	Overpass / OSM	No — HTTP query
Serial to knob	Web Serial API	Yes — direct USB
The Web Serial API is actually the most novel one for automotive HMI research — direct browser-to-hardware communication without any driver or middleware, which is what makes your knob and laptop screen stay perfectly synchronised. That is genuinely worth highlighting in the thesis as it is a recent Chrome addition (2021) and most HMI research still assumes a backend server in between.
